                        <hi rendition="#u">Larix</hi> a very distinct species from <lb/>the
                    Neighbourhood of <hi rendition="#u">Almora</hi>. The 3-d belongs to the section
                        <lb/><hi rendition="#u">Pinus</hi>, named by me &amp; <persName key="H0006224"><choice>
                            <abbr>Dr</abbr>
                            <expan>Doctor</expan>
                        </choice> Wallich</persName>, Pinus excelsa, akin to Pinus <lb/>strobus but
                    with characters widely different as you hereafter <lb/>see. The Species
                    mentioned by <persName key="H0003962">Thunberg</persName> in <seg type="comment">
                        <orig>Flora Japonica</orig>
                        <note xml:id="nscn_tzs_4x"><ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/avh-r/items/collectionKey/NFW9QRUD/itemKey/5UQ9ZV6R">Thunberg 1784</ref>.</note>
                    </seg><choice>
                        <reg>,</reg>
                    </choice> I <lb/>have no doubt will all prove very different from those <lb/>of
                        <placeName key="H0005696">Europe</placeName> &amp; <placeName key="H0001698"><choice>
                            <abbr>N.</abbr>
                            <expan>North</expan>
                        </choice> America</placeName><choice>
                        <orig>.</orig>
                        <reg>,</reg>
                    </choice> his <hi rendition="#u"><choice>
                            <abbr>P.</abbr>
                            <expan>Pinus</expan>
                        </choice></hi>
                    <hi rendition="#u">strobus</hi>. may possibly be the <lb/>same with my <choice>
                        <abbr>P.</abbr>
                        <expan>Pinus</expan>
                    </choice> excelsa, and his <hi rendition="#u"><choice>
                            <abbr>P.</abbr>
                            <expan>Pinus</expan>
                        </choice></hi>
                    <hi rendition="#u">Larix</hi>, the same with <lb/>mine from Almara<choice>
                        <orig>.</orig>
                        <reg>,</reg>
                    </choice> as <choice>
                        <sic>their</sic>
                        <corr cert="high">there</corr>
                    </choice> are many plants common to <lb/>both countries in <placeName key="H0001596">Nepal</placeName>. I have here sent you some of <persName key="H0006224"><choice>
                            <abbr>Dr.</abbr>
                            <expan>Doctor</expan>
                        </choice>
                        <hi rendition="#u"><lb/>Wallichs</hi></persName> Letters to me relating to
                        <placeName key="H0001596">Nepal</placeName>, which I hope will afford
                    <lb/>some pleasure, and which I will be obliged by returning to me <lb/>at your
                    leisure when an opportunity offers. When are <supplied cert="high">we</supplied>
                    to see <seg type="comment">
                        <orig>your <lb/><pb n="4v" facs="http://content.staatsbibliothek-berlin.de/dms/PPN826366848/500/0/00000008"/>Map of <hi rendition="#u">New</hi>
                            <hi rendition="#u">Granada</hi></orig>
                        <note xml:id="nmys_wqb_px">Humboldts „Carte générale de Colombia“ erschien
                            1825 mit der fünften Lieferung als Planche 22 von <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/avh-r/items/collectionKey/NFW9QRUD/itemKey/RKBBPG4A/q/atlas">Humboldt 1814-1834</ref> (vgl. <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/avh-r/items/collectionKey/NFW9QRUD/itemKey/384RP7BM/q/fiedler">Fiedler/Leitner 2000</ref>, 162).</note>
                    </seg>. <seg type="comment">
                        <orig>I am anxiously waiting for the 5. volume <lb/>of your <hi rendition="#u">Personal</hi>
                            <hi rendition="#u">Narrative</hi></orig>
                        <note xml:id="norp_x2t_4x">Der fünfte Band von <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/avh-r/items/collectionKey/NFW9QRUD/itemKey/QNXRGGR7">Humboldt 1814-1829</ref> erschien 1821. Vgl. <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/avh-r/items/collectionKey/NFW9QRUD/itemKey/384RP7BM/q/Fiedler">Fiedler/Leitner 2000</ref>, 104.</note>
                    </seg>, which I understand from Messrs. <lb/>Longman &amp; Co. is to be
                    published here about christmas. Poor <persName key="H0002227"><choice>
                            <abbr><lb/>Mr</abbr>
                            <expan>Mister</expan>
                        </choice> Pursh</persName> Author of the <seg type="comment">
                        <orig><hi rendition="#u">Flora</hi>
                            <hi rendition="#u">Americae</hi>
                            <choice>
                                <abbr><hi rendition="#u">Septentr</hi>.</abbr>
                                <expan>Septentrionalis</expan>
                            </choice></orig>
                        <note xml:id="nnyg_tj4_4x"><ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/avh-r/items/collectionKey/NFW9QRUD/itemKey/M4TNQJF9">Pursh 1814</ref>.</note>
                    </seg> is no more. His widow <lb/>has just arrived from <placeName key="H0000345"><hi rendition="#u">Canada</hi></placeName>, with a very
                    extensive collection of <lb/>specimens of plants from that Country which is now
                    in my possession. <lb/><choice>
                        <orig>had</orig>
                        <reg>Had</reg>
                    </choice> he lived it was his intention to publish a Flora of <placeName key="H0000345">Canada</placeName>, for <lb/>which he had collected ample
                    materials. I beg you will present <lb/>my kindest respects to <persName key="H0001517"><choice>
                            <abbr>Mr</abbr>
                            <expan>Mister</expan>
                        </choice> Kunth</persName>. Is <choice>
                        <sic>their</sic>
                        <corr cert="high">there</corr>
                    </choice> any hopes of <choice>
                        <sic>of</sic>
                        <corr type="deleted"/>
                    </choice> you seeing <lb/>you &amp; him in this Country soon. <add place="superlinear"><metamark><choice>
                                <orig>since</orig>
                                <reg>Since</reg>
                            </choice> writing the above </metamark></add>I have just received a very
                    <lb/>long and interesting Letter from my friend <persName key="H0012873"><hi rendition="#u">Professor</hi>
                        <hi rendition="#u">DeCandolle</hi></persName>
                    <lb/>who mentions that the <choice>
                        <abbr>2<hi rendition="#u"><hi rendition="#sup">d</hi></hi></abbr>
                        <expan>second</expan>
                    </choice>
                    <choice>
                        <abbr>vo.</abbr>
                        <expan>volume</expan>
                    </choice> of his <seg type="comment">
                        <orig>Systema <choice>
                                <abbr>Veget.</abbr>
                                <expan>Vegetabilium</expan>
                            </choice></orig>
                        <note xml:id="nht1_xys_4x"><ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/avh-r/items/collectionKey/NFW9QRUD/itemKey/IJR4MGGU">Candolle 1818-1820, II</ref>.</note>
                    </seg> will be <lb/>out in a Month from the date of his Letter. 26 <choice>
                        <abbr>oct</abbr>
                        <expan>October</expan>
                    </choice>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours very Sincerely</salute>
                    <signed>Alymer Bourke Lambert.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
            <postscript>
                <p>P. S. I was extremely sorry, at not having the pleasure of seeing <lb/>your
                    Friend <persName key="H0012928"><choice>
                            <abbr>Dr.</abbr>
                            <expan>Doctor</expan>
                        </choice> Caspar</persName>. who I beg you will give my compliments <lb/>to.
                    I have just had a very splendid <placeName key="H0008847">Mexican</placeName> plant which <lb/>has flowered in my Hothouse, it is
                    nearly allied to Bromelia <lb/>paniculigera of <persName key="H0016188">Swartz</persName><choice>
                        <orig>.</orig>
                        <reg>,</reg>
                    </choice> at least of the same genus with it<choice>
                        <orig>.</orig>
                        <reg>,</reg>
                    </choice> very <lb/>different from Bromelia. <choice>
                        <orig>the</orig>
                        <reg>The</reg>
                    </choice> flowers are white edged with crimson <lb/>in large panicles. The <subst>
                        <del rendition="#s">floral</del>
                        <add place="superlinear">stem</add>
                    </subst> leaves from 2 to 3 feet long of a beautiful <lb/>crimson.<lb/></p>
            </postscript>
